Public procurement of works and prevention of corruption
Joint report of the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Court of Auditors of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and overview
Public procurement of services is of great importance both to the state and to the economy.
The role of the State is to use public funds in the most economical and economical way possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the procurement of services by contracting authorities is an important element in the creation of a single economic area.
In order to be able to ensure largely unrestricted competition across borders, contracting authorities will have to comply with EU rules when awarding contracts above certain value limits (thresholds).
To this end, the EU Member States have to transpose and apply EU public procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Under the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to decide how to award public contracts.
The provision of services is also an area prone to corruption.
Due to the generally high potential for damage, the contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and improper favours in the awarding of their contracts.
The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Court of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed in January 2011 to carry out parallel audits both on the EU-wide award of construction services and on the prevention of corruption.
The audits focused on the application of EU public procurement law, which is transposed into national legislation, and on the prevention of corruption in the awarding of construction, road and transport infrastructure contracts.
Procurement below the EU thresholds has also been included in the considerations with a view to preventing corruption.
The audit results of both Court of Auditors are summarised in this Joint Report.
The report should also be addressed to international institutions, such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
The evaluations of the Federal Court of Auditors on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional audits, which he carried out in 2011 / 2012 with the building authorities, which are responsible for the construction of roads and the construction of the federal government in Germany.
For example, he examined the construction of motorways as well as large construction projects.
In addition, the Bundesrechnungshof used results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on test knowledge from 2008 to 2011. The tests covered construction activities in road construction, rail construction, water construction, construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) as well as other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the awarding of federal public contracts is mainly carried out by the construction authorities of the Länder.
In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for the procurement of transport infrastructure.
In the construction sector, procurement is carried out on a decentralised basis by those bodies that make use of state budgetary resources.
In both countries, freelancers are also involved in sub-sectors of procurement procedures.
When comparing the evaluations, account must be taken of differences in procurement law and in the market structure for construction services in both countries.
Building the public procurement system in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is defined in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures, which are limited to national areas, are governed by budgetary law and administrative rules based on it.
In addition, there are many additional individual rules for both EU-wide and national public procurement through internal administrative provisions,
such as the so-called "procurement manuals" of the federal government, in which the statutory requirements are supplemented or more precisely formulated in accordance with the case law of procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Procurement Act and the other statutory provisions, which apply both above and below the EU thresholds.
The law on public procurement was substantially amended in 2012.
The new rules increased transparency in the handling of public funds, allowed greater competition and limited the possibility of corruption in the procurement process.
Broad principles of public procurement law in both countries
In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiation procedure apply in particular to EU-wide awards.
In Germany, measures below the EU threshold are subject to national tendering methods (public tendering, limited tendering, freelance procurement), which broadly correspond to the EU-wide tendering methods mentioned above.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the primacy of the open procedure (for awards to be carried out throughout the EU) and the principle of the public tender (for national awards).
In the open procedure and in the public tender process, any interested company can submit an offer.
Another essential feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized enterprises.
The main purpose of this is to divide an overall construction project into specialist and partial units.
The individual allocation of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the above features of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.
More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are active in Germany.
In the Czech Republic, the EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable for construction projects below the EU threshold.
An exception to this is the simplified procedure, where a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law, in line with EU law, contains provisions to conclude contracts where competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.
The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow the contracting authorities to choose between the open and the non-open procedure.
There are more than 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 are companies with 20 or more employees.
