The above-mentioned data show that the parallel audits of both countries are aimed at a significant part of public procurement, that the prevention of corruption to be observed in all awards is of great financial importance and that the open procedure and public tendering are of paramount importance in awarding the contracts.
Summary of the results of the parallel tests
The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Court of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits in their countries on the EU-wide award of construction services and on the prevention of corruption.
In this context, the working groups of both Court of Auditors compared the relevant legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and in Germany as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of construction and road construction.
The main findings were as follows:
The EU Directives on the award of construction services by public authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (Nr. 1 and 3.1).
In addition to the EU requirements, the anti-corruption provisions of both countries also serve to prevent corruption, with partial differences in their priorities and details (no. 3.2).
In both countries, an essential requirement of the tender documents is that they must contain all the information necessary for an appropriate bid to be made.
The performance descriptions must be neutral and must not contain any restrictions on betting or advertising.
In Germany, the procurement documents have largely complied with these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it remains a problem to adequately determine the object of the contract.
In Germany, construction work should be divided into lots as far as possible in order to promote competition.
According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.
NKÚ found in its audits, in particular in the field of road construction, that the award of large-scale services without lots or with very large lots can affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.
Restrictions on market potential can lead to substantial cost increases and risk price or other agreements.
In accordance with the provisions of both countries, the contracting authorities may, under certain conditions, agree in principle with the companies already contracted to provide additional or modified services which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (no. 4.1).
Most of the requirements for setting the type of tender have been complied with in both countries.
Under the rules of the Czech Republic, contracting authorities are free to choose between open and non-open procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the primacy of the open procedure in the case of EU-wide procurement or of the public tender, which corresponds to the open procedure in the case of national procurement, is enshrined in law and budget law.
This will allow more companies to bid.
This reduces the risk of corruption, makes it more difficult for bidders to collude on prices and produces the most economic results.
In the case of construction projects whose estimated total order values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited building authorities generally awarded construction services throughout Europe.
The correct estimation of the expected order value is an essential basis in the choice of the correct procurement method.
In Germany, cost databases are used for cost investigations in public buildings, in particular in the construction sector,
based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective instrument (No. 4.2).
Preliminary information and announcements are to be published in the case of works to be awarded throughout Europe. This is intended to strengthen competition by allowing interested companies to prepare for the planned awards at an early stage.
As a rule, the audited building authorities complied with this requirement.
In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or lack of controls may affect competition (no. 4.3).
The selection of candidates for participation in non-public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.
Under EU law, the number of invited applicants must be high enough to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be disclosed in advance.
In addition to the EU requirements, contracting authorities in both countries are to switch as often as possible among the companies to be challenged in the selection of candidates.
In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are sometimes very detailed guidelines in Germany.
In some cases, the audited administrations failed to take these requirements into account.
In the Czech Republic, decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (No. 4.4).
In both countries, in the interests of fair competition, it is necessary to ensure that the same information is given to the companies interested in submitting an offer during the tender period.
A contact between these companies with each other and with freelancers who were involved in the preparation of the service description is to be avoided as far as possible in order to avoid anti-competitive agreements.
The relevant regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
However, the audited building authorities in Germany partially failed to comply with these requirements (No. 4.5).
In both countries, particular attention should be paid to the multi-eyes principle and the principle of transparency when opening offers.
The requirements for marking, documentation, custody and secrecy of the offers are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are defined in particular detail in Germany.
The tests in both countries yielded only a few complaints (No. 4.6).
Examination and evaluation of the offers are defined in both countries by requirements for the organization of training and leave.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.
For example, awarding agencies passed on offers for review to third parties without having to look through the offers beforehand and to document conspicuous features sufficiently.
The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (no. 4.7).
At the end of the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies involved in the competition will be informed of the intended award before it is awarded.
This possibility of legal protection also has a preventive function against corrupt behaviour.
The Czech Republic also provides for the possibility of judicial review of non-EU procurement procedures.
Only in a few cases did the contracting authorities not comply with the prescribed deadlines in the awarding of contracts or deviate from the content of the bidders' offer (no. 4.8).
Documentation of tendering procedures was not always complete or comprehensible to the audited building authorities in both countries.
In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in the procurement notices of some procedures.
Also, some of the identified shortcomings diminished the corruption-prevention function of the documentation.
The contracting authorities of both countries largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (no. 4.9).
Fundamental principles of EU public procurement law and the prevention of corruption
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition with the free movement of services and goods within the European Union, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted inter alia the Procurement Coordination Directive and the Remedies Directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the 8 Member States.
The general tendering principles of the European Union are, in particular, the principle of competition, the principle of equal treatment and the prohibition of discrimination, as well as the principle of transparency.
In order to achieve these objectives, the Procurement Coordination Directive lays down specific rules for construction works to be carried out across the EU.
In order to do so, the estimated volume of orders must reach or exceed the current EUR 5.000.000.
The provisions concern in particular the content of the tender documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the observance of deadlines, inter alia, for the receipt of the bids, the documentation of the tender procedure, the requirements that may be imposed on the qualifications of the applicants, and the Directive on the right of appeal, which forms the basis for the legal protection of applicants and bidders.
In the event of possible breaches of public procurement law, interested undertakings may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review procedures.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the European Union directives into national law.
Preventing corruption
The importance of preventing corruption
In both countries there is no legal definition of corruption.
In general, corruption is the abuse of a position of trust for private gain,
which, as a rule, is initiated by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hinder competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of world economic output.
In the area of the European Union, the level of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of public procurement, restrictive agreements or unfair practices may call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public authorities.
They will have to review the structure and organisation of their administrations in areas that are particularly vulnerable to corruption, in order to ensure that they are adequately protected against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works is generally considered to be a particularly sensitive area of work to corruption.
Measures to prevent corruption
In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and bribery as well as the taking and approval of benefits - is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
For the prevention of corruption, the Federal Government has issued a directive and recommendations on the prevention of corruption in the federal administration. Thereafter, the following principles must be observed for the procurement sector in addition to the risk analysis: primacy of public tenders and open procedures, more eyes and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, award and billing, precise and complete documentation of procurement procedures.
In addition, further anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into the public procurement rules.
In 2011, the competent Federal Ministry for Public Procurement introduced an electronically supported control system in the area of national highways,
with the award data - such as the estimated costs and the order amounts - as well as data on the participating freelance workers are collected throughout the country and evaluated for conspicuous differences.
Corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law in the Czech Republic.
The legal requirements for transparency and equal treatment of tenderers, as well as the prohibition of any discrimination, form the main basis for the prevention of corruption.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Government has set out anti-corruption measures in an anti-corruption strategy paper for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures it recommends have already been transposed into national procurement law and corresponding administrative provisions 14.
The main provisions of the new legislation are as follows: lowering the thresholds for smaller contracts, the obligation to notify the award office beforehand, including the reasons for tendering, the prohibition of limiting the number of tenderers in open procedures and thus the elimination of the possibility of selecting tenderers by lottery, the introduction of the obligation to publish the tender documents and all annexes, and the introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Examination results on the different phases of the procurement procedure
Procurement documents
Procurement documents The tender documents must contain all the information the bidders need for an appropriate bid.
In particular, the procurement documents must allow for accurate calculation.
Bidders must not be entrusted with risks that they cannot calculate.
The procurement documents consist in particular of the description of the services and the contractual conditions.
They also contain the requirements to prove the qualification (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria which are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law on procurement documents are addressed in particular to technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should restrict competition as little as possible.
The performance description must be product-neutral.
Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the performance description is only permissible under strict conditions.
Avoiding anti-competitive requirements in procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.
In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the tender documents must be avoided, as it opens up room for speculation in the preparation of the bids and for manipulation in their valuation.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar rules In both countries, EU legislation on technical specifications has been transposed into national law.
In principle, the services are to be advertised in a product-neutral manner without factory specifications.
In the service descriptions, the individual services must, as a rule, be subdivided into performance units with the respective quantities detailed.
Here the prices are to be agreed on the basis of power units (e.g. B. Euro per m ² or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases may services be defined by functional targets.
In any case, the performance descriptions must be complete and unambiguous.
They must contain precise quantities and must not include services where it is not clear whether they are needed.
Compensation according to lump sums or time spent is to be avoided if possible.
The aim of these provisions is to prevent speculation and manipulation based on undefined requirements in the procurement documents.
The descriptions of services must enable bidders to prepare their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The call for tenders shall not be made public until the tender documents have been completed.
Different rules for Vonn
There is no obligation in the Czech Republic to tender for construction services in lots.
If it is possible according to the type of service to be commissioned, public procurement agencies can divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, construction services are generally divided into lots, separated by the quantity (partial) and / or by type or subject (skilled).
The aim is to enable small and medium-sized enterprises to participate in competition, to increase the number of possible suppliers and to make it more difficult for them to collude on prices.
This type of award is generally considered to be the most economical.
Valuation criteria in the Czech Republic must be indicated in the procurement documents, both in the EU-wide and in the national procedures.
The aim is to make it completely and conclusively clear to the applicants by which criteria their offers are to be evaluated.
In Germany, the indication of evaluation criteria in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the procurement documents, is only mandatory in the case of EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria must only be set out in an internal administrative award note.
Procurement documents, which are prepared by commissioned freelancers, may not contain references to these offices or involved planners or surveyors in Germany with the civil engineering and some road construction administrations.
The aim is to prevent individual companies from obtaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the client's knowledge about the contact with these freelancers.
This is also the reason why freelancers are not allowed to send out procurement documents or to submit planning documents for inspection.
The client is the sole contact of the companies.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic on this matter.
Additional or modified services that prove to be necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements) almost always accrue to large construction projects.
In both countries, the legislation allows, to a certain extent, supplementary contracts to be awarded to the company already contracted, without the need for a public procurement procedure.
According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, the remuneration of the supplementary services may not exceed half of the main contract.
In addition, the additional services may not be separated from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20% for awarding such contracts without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of a delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already under way.
If supplementary services are also transferred to the already contracted company, according to the regulations in Germany an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is not possible in principle.
When determining the remuneration for the additional services, it is rather to be assumed that the agreed prices and the basis for calculating the price of the order that has already been awarded are the same.
In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, reduced quantities cannot be offset with additional supplementary services.
