A summary of the findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly consistent in both countries and take into account the EU requirements.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and the prevention of corruption.
For example, the requirement for the sufficient determination of the performance descriptions should enable the bidders to calculate and prepare their offers in an appropriate manner,
protect the client from additional services to be agreed upon afterwards and also limit the scope for speculation.
In Germany, the common basic requirements for procurement documents are supplemented by rules aimed at further reducing restrictions on competition and the possibility of manipulation.
In the Czech Republic, there are no such requirements, but the publication of the evaluation criteria in non-EU procurement procedures will increase transparency.
The requirements for the description of performance have largely been met in both countries.
In some cases, however, derogations had to be objected to, which may also have led to restrictions on competition.
The German requirement for the formation of lots encourages competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the audit findings of NKÚ, the awarding of large-scale services without lots or with very large lots may lead to restrictions on the scope of suppliers to only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements imposed on road construction in the Czech Republic have meant that public contracts are awarded only to a small number of suppliers and that small and medium-sized enterprises are not allowed to compete.
Also, a limited number of competitors often leads to higher prices and increases the risk of price or other collusion.
In the case of the award and remuneration of additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches in both countries differ.
Under EU and German rules, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main contract can be awarded under certain conditions without a public procurement procedure.
In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20%, up to which additional services can be awarded to the original contractor in the negotiation procedure without notice.
