Setting the type of contract and taking the EU threshold into account
By determining the method of awarding the contract, the contracting authority determines the size of the number of companies participating in the competition.
It can leave the range of possible candidates and bidders largely unrestricted, for example by choosing an open procedure, or by limiting the number of non-public procurement procedures.
For construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded, pan-European tendering procedures are applicable.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
When choosing the type of contract, the contracting authority has to take account in particular of European competition and transparency requirements.
If the estimated total order value of the construction services of a project is or is above the current EU threshold of EUR 5.000,000, the construction services are generally to be awarded Europe-wide in accordance with open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
In the case of construction projects that reach or exceed the EU threshold, the contracting authority may deviate to a limited extent from the principle of pan-European procurement and may award works in national procurement procedures, provided that the estimated contract value of the relevant lot is less than EUR 1,000,000 and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the estimated total order value of all construction contracts.
A single construction project must not be divided into individual measures without compelling reason or deliberately estimated at too low a cost to avoid the obligation to award construction services in principle throughout Europe.
As restrictions on competition substantially increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of award method is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The detailed justification of the type of award chosen and the examination of the applicability of the EU procurement rules are important elements of the documentation of the award procedure.
Rules of German and Czech public procurement law
Same or similar arrangements
Both countries have fully transposed the EU rules on procurement procedures and the threshold into national law.
Different rules for Vonn
The Czech Republic has also transferred the fundamental equivalence of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU Directive to its public works contracts, which are not subject to the EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and non-open procedures, without the decision having to be documented or substantiated. However, other procedures are only possible under certain statutory conditions.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure or - in the case of national tenders - the public tendering principle takes precedence. This is determined by the law on budgets and procurement as well as by the directives on the prevention of corruption.
Other types of tendering - such as the non-open procedure or the restricted tender - are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated by public procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be justifiably justified and documented.
The principle of the primacy of the open procedure or of the public call for tenders is intended to ensure that competition is as open as possible, to prevent the possibility of manipulation by focusing on certain tenderers and to make it more difficult for bidders to collude on prices.
The principle of a public tender is a central element in the prevention of corruption in Germany.
The correct estimation of the expected order value is an essential basis in the choice of the correct procurement method.
The construction services in Germany can use planning and cost databases of public administrations as well as other organisations to determine the likely costs in the area of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. The databases contain, among other things, cost characteristics for building categories, use units, construction elements or individual construction services.
On the basis of such cost characteristics, the estimated order value of a planned project or a construction performance to be awarded can be determined.
In Germany, the corresponding cost databases for road construction have only been used by some building authorities.
However, a nationwide introduction for all road authorities is foreseen.
Contracting agencies in the Czech Republic cannot rely on central databases or average price assessments of comparable construction projects to determine the likely costs of construction services.
Rather, in most cases, the cost assessments are based on estimates made by the financing authority or on the amount of funds made available to the construction service.
Measures to standardize cost determination procedures are still in the early stages.
As part of the anti-corruption plan for 2011-2012, the relevant ministries were mandated to create a database for standardised building materials and materials.
