Key test results BRH
Selection of the award procedure
The surveyed contracting authorities wrote out the construction work largely in an open procedure or in a public tender and thus followed the budgetary and procurement regulations.
In 2011, 59.5% of the construction services provided by the federal government in the construction sector were advertised publicly or in open procedures.
In road construction, this figure stood at 94.8%.
The choice of non-public tendering methods sometimes lacked detailed reasons as to why the tendering authorities had to deviate from the principle of an open procedure or of a public tender.
In a cross-sectional investigation, based on more than 16,000 procurement procedures, the BRH found that the types of non-public procurement, compared with the open procedures and public tenders, have significant disadvantages in terms of competition and increase the risk of manipulation and corruption.
In the construction sector, more than twice as many tenders were submitted to public tenders as in the case of restricted tenders and almost three times as many bids as in the case of freehold tenders.
The study also showed that bidding prices were on average 6% or 10% higher for limited tenders and freeholds than for public tenders.
Parallel investigations by the Federal Ministry of Building and a National Audit Office confirmed the economic differences between public and non-public procurement schemes.
The Federal Ministry of Building and Construction even found twice as high differences between public and non-public procurement procedures in the results of its studies on economic efficiency.
Taking the EU threshold into account
In the case of the construction projects for which they had identified an expected total order amount of more than EUR 5.000,000, the contracting authorities audited generally drew up procurement plans in which they defined the works to be awarded in accordance with EU and national procurement procedures.
According to the procurement plans, this meant that more than 80% of construction work was to be awarded throughout the EU.
It was not possible to avoid the obligation to award EU-wide contracts by underestimating costs.
However, partly as a result of incorrect calculations, the minimum share of EU-wide procurement procedures actually fell short.
During the construction phase, some contracting authorities improperly changed the terms of their procurement plans.
They did not justify these changes and did not demonstrate that the minimum share of EU-wide procurement procedures had been maintained.
For most of the construction projects audited, the share of EU-wide levies was generally lower than foreseen under the procurement plan, according to the results.
In some cases, contracting authorities failed to comply with the requirement to tender all €1,000,000 or more of single lots in EU-wide procedures for construction projects above the EU threshold,
and chose national procedures instead.
