Choice of procurement method
In the case of several large construction projects, such as the construction of some sections of motorway, construction projects in the context of a major sporting event and housing projects, the contracting authorities divided construction work into several sub-contracts, although these services were similar or comparable.
As a result of these divisions, the individual services were no longer above the threshold value and were subsequently awarded in simplified procedures or even in breach of legal requirements.
Calculation methods for the estimated order value
In the case of road construction, the existing price databases in this area were only an inadequate instrument for determining the expected order values.
The data were based on construction projects that had just been completed, but there were indications of a lack of efficiency, unnecessary additional performance expenditure or excessive profits for the companies commissioned.
For three sections of a motorway ring, the actual prices were about 37% lower than the estimated order values determined by the database.
In the meantime, the Ministry of Transport revised the databases in order to take into account not only the supply prices of the last few years, but also comparable market prices and indices of price increases in the construction sector.
In the construction sector, the expected order values were based on the estimated cost values of the project architects or on estimates from investors.
The actual order values differed greatly from the estimates.
The estimated price for the conversion or expansion of a large library was double the later agreed order value, but eight additions during construction led to a cost increase of EUR 2.1 million or 27%.
Similarly, the actual order value for the construction of a library depot was 33% lower than the estimated price, with cost increases during the construction phase also occurring.
In other cases, the bid prices exceeded the estimates and increased during the construction phase.
In the case of the construction of a large library, the estimated price was exceeded by EUR 16 million or 22%. In the case of the construction of a judicial building, the costs increased disproportionately at 139%, as the usable area had expanded by only 12%.
A summary of the findings
Both countries have transposed into national law the EU rules on setting the type of procurement and taking into account the EU threshold, so the respective rules are broadly in line.
However, the priority given in Germany to the open procedure or the public tender goes beyond the EU requirements and the rules in force in the Czech Republic.
Compared to non-public tendering procedures, more companies will be able to compete in public procedures or public tenders.
Public procurement procedures lead to a higher number of bids and to the most economic results.
The risk of corruption will be significantly improved by ensuring that the field of candidates is not constrained by manipulation-prone provisions of the contracting authority and by making it more difficult for bidders to collude on prices.
The investigations have confirmed the advantages of the primacy of the open procedure or the public tender in Germany.
Czech legislation allows contracting authorities to award contracts on an open or non-open basis.
According to the latest changes in procurement law, the number of bidders may no longer be limited in procedures involving previous competition.
This means that the non-open procedure is now very similar to the open procedure.
In Germany, the awarding authorities have largely complied with the rules on the primacy of the open procedure or the public tender. In the Czech Republic, some services have been inadvertently divided up in order to circumvent the rules on the choice of award method.
When the EU threshold was taken into account, errors had to be identified in Germany, which meant that the minimum share of benefits tendered across the EU was below.
In the Czech Republic, there is still no satisfactory solution for correctly calculating the estimated costs of construction and construction projects.
Building authorities should, if necessary, carry out further checks to ensure that the requirements for the choice of procurement method and the scope of services to be advertised throughout the EU are complied with or that the conditions for accurate cost assessments are created.
