Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
The EU guidelines provide for a multi-stage procedure:
Firstly, the suitability of the bidders must be established.
Bidders must be economically and financially capable and possess the necessary professional and technical expertise.
Companies which have been convicted of bribery or fraud offences, for example, are excluded from taking part in the award procedure.
The bids of the non-excluded tenderers are to be examined computationally, technically and economically and to be evaluated on the basis of the previously announced award criteria.
The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer. Offers with unusually low prices have to be examined particularly by the client.
The examination and evaluation of the tenders is a particularly susceptible phase of the tendering procedure.
For example, bidders may be unfairly excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements may be left in competition.
By favoring or discriminating against bidders, the result of the valuation can be inadvertently impaired and thus the establishment of the most economically advantageous offer can be prevented.
The awarding authority must therefore take special precautions to ensure that the persons entrusted with the examination and assessment meet the requirements of integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure that the procedure and the decisions taken are transparent and comprehensible.
