A summary of the findings
The rules for examining and evaluating offers in both countries are in line with EU requirements.
However, the rules differ on the details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved.
In Germany, the process is more regulated than in the Czech Republic by means of detailed requirements, in particular regarding the implementation of the "more eyes" principle and the protection of offers.
The same applies to the requirements on the basis of which the adequacy of the prices offered must be assessed.
In both countries, some of the tendering procedures examined showed that significant procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of the tenders were not or were insufficiently documented.
Without traceability and transparency of the examination and evaluation decisions, however, possible manipulative interventions are favoured.
A particularly serious defect was the handing over of all offers to third parties, without the public contracting authority having previously sufficiently reviewed and documented the offers and thus protected them from possible manipulation in the further procedure.
If the contracting authority has the task of verifying and evaluating the offers carried out by third parties, sufficient precautions and an increased control effort are required in order to counter the increased risk of manipulation.
In assessing the adequacy of the prices, the audited services in Germany have not always made full use of the instruments provided and have not sufficiently examined the price structure of the offers.
In the Czech Republic, objections arose mainly in relation to the aptitude test and the application of the evaluation criteria.
