Comprehensive evaluation and recommendations
The parallel audits of the NKÚ and the BRH have focused on two main areas, which in the Czech Republic and in Germany are essential for public procurement of works: the application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The requirements of EU law will enable cross-border competition to create a single European market.
Corruption prevention measures are not only aimed at preventing or at least reducing corruption; they are also aimed at preventing economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The auditing experience of the two Court of Auditors on the application of public procurement rules in both countries and the comparison of these rules reveals similarities and differences which may be helpful for both countries in developing their procurement law and its application.
Application of EU procurement rules
Both countries have transposed the EU's rules on the award of construction services into their national legislation.
In this way, the Czech Republic and Germany have an important common basis for awarding works and taking into account the essential competitive requirements, the equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of procurement procedures.
The building authorities of both countries have, in some cases very extensively, supplemented these bids with further administrative provisions.
The Czech Republic has also to a large extent transferred the requirements for construction services to be awarded throughout the EU to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the investigations carried out by the Court of Auditors have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The building management in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the problems identified in implementing the EU requirements.
In particular, the tests carried out in the Czech Republic have shown that there are risks to the economic viability of public procurement.
For example, incomplete performance descriptions required additional services, which were often awarded in violation of the law. Moreover, cost assessments were generally inadequately prepared. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, especially in transport construction.
Preventing corruption
The aim of the investigations was not to uncover cases of corruption,
also because the Court of Auditors does not have the necessary instruments for this purpose.
However, the Court of Auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken steps to prevent corruption and manipulation in the procurement of works and how these measures are applied.
Both countries have different priorities when it comes to preventing corruption.
In particular, the German rules provide for largely unrestricted competition, transparency and controls as key elements in the prevention of corruption.
The main aim of the Czech rules is to increase the transparency of procedures.
