The Czech Republic adopted an anti-corruption strategy at government level, in which the area of public procurement is the main component.
The Procurement Act and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
The audits of NKÚ took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions are likely to be effective measures for improvement, as the contracting authorities will have to justify the profitability of the orders, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the nature of the evaluations, and will have to document and publish all these aspects properly.
The recommendations include:
The NKÚ and the BRH give a generally positive assessment of the implementation of the EU requirements.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that EU bids for competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and ideological potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the provision of construction services, both Court of Auditors have called on the building authorities in their countries to continue and, if necessary, to improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to be able to take appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the share of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
Greater division of building services into lots can also have a favourable effect on bid prices, provided that this results in greater competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for efficient procurement by public purchasers.
In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised building authorities. In the Czech Republic, however, these tasks - with the exception of transport projects - are carried out by the departments themselves or by contractors commissioned by them.
The Court of Auditors of both countries has the concern, even after the conclusion of their joint project, to further develop the findings which are important to them in each case and, if necessary, to refer them to the parliament and government of their country.
Both Court of Auditors are also convinced that the principles of public procurement as set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at international level to the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), because the principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to effectively combat corruption and to ensure the efficient award of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
